Title: Unsafe narrowing cast in concentrated liquidity AMM burn() silently truncates liquidity delta allowing attacker to steal pool tokens
Impact: HIGH
Protocol: Concentrated Liquidity AMM

The burn() function in a concentrated liquidity pool performs an unsafe narrowing cast when updating reserve accounting. After computing token amounts and fees through internal helpers, the function casts uint256 fee values to uint128 without any overflow check. When an attacker crafts a position such that the intermediate fee value exceeds type(uint128).max, Solidity's explicit cast silently truncates the value, causing the reserve to be decremented by a far smaller amount than the tokens actually transferred out.

File: ConcentratedLiquidityPool.sol

231 : function burn(bytes calldata data) public lock returns (IPool.TokenAmount[] memory withdrawnAmounts) {
232 :     (int24 lower, int24 upper, uint128 amount, address recipient, bool unwrapBento) = abi.decode(
233 :         data, (int24, int24, uint128, address, bool)
234 :     );
245 :     (uint256 amount0, uint256 amount1) = _getAmountsForLiquidity(priceLower, priceUpper, currentPrice, uint256(amount));
252 :     (uint256 feesAmount0, uint256 feesAmount1) = _updatePosition(msg.sender, lower, upper, -int128(amount));
254 :     unchecked {
255 :         amount0 += feesAmount0;
256 :         amount1 += feesAmount1;
257 :     }
263 :     unchecked {
264 :@>      reserveBalance0 -= uint128(feesAmount0);  // BUG: silent truncation if feesAmount0 > type(uint128).max
265 :@>      reserveBalance1 -= uint128(feesAmount1);  // BUG: silent truncation if feesAmount1 > type(uint128).max
266 :     }
268 :     _transferBothTokens(recipient, amount0, amount1, unwrapBento);
269 : }

The transfer sends the full amount0/amount1 (including feesAmount0/feesAmount1) to the recipient, but the reserve is only decremented by the truncated uint128 value. This inflates the apparent pool reserves and breaks all subsequent accounting.

Impact: Attacker drains pool tokens by exploiting the reserve/transfer mismatch created by the silent uint128 cast truncation.

Recommended mitigation: Add require(feesAmount0 <= type(uint128).max) before the cast, or use SafeCast.toUint128().

Title: Concentrated liquidity position manager burn() propagates incorrect token amounts from underlying pool causing LP to receive less than entitled
Impact: HIGH
Protocol: Concentrated Liquidity Position Manager

The NFT position manager burn() calls the underlying pool's burn() to remove liquidity, but the returned token amounts are not correctly captured or validated. The position manager passes the recipient address directly to pool.burn(), so the pool transfers tokens internally — but the position manager does not verify or forward the actual returned amounts. LPs who burn their NFT positions may receive incorrect token amounts.

File: ConcentratedLiquidityPosition.sol

 54 : function burn(
 55 :     uint256 tokenId,
 56 :     uint128 amount,
 57 :     address recipient,
 58 :     bool unwrapBento
 59 : ) external {
 60 :     require(msg.sender == ownerOf[tokenId], "NOT_ID_OWNER");
 61 :     Position storage position = positions[tokenId];
 62 :     if (position.liquidity < amount) amount = position.liquidity;
 63 :
 64 :@>  position.pool.burn(abi.encode(position.lower, position.upper, amount, recipient, unwrapBento));
 65 :     // BUG: return value IPool.TokenAmount[] ignored — actual withdrawn amounts not captured
 66 :     // The pool transfers tokens directly to recipient, bypassing position manager validation
 67 :     // amount0 and amount1 actually withdrawn are never verified
 68 :
 69 :     if (amount < position.liquidity) {
 70 :         position.liquidity -= amount;
 71 :     } else {
 72 :         delete positions[tokenId];
 73 :         _burn(tokenId);
 74 :     }
 75 : }

Because pool.burn() transfers to recipient directly and the return value is discarded, there is no way for the position manager to verify amounts or emit accurate events. If the pool returns different amounts than expected (e.g., due to rounding or fee accounting), the position manager silently accepts the discrepancy.

Impact: LP funds may be permanently underpaid on every burn() call through the NFT position manager.

Recommended mitigation: Capture the return value of pool.burn() and verify that withdrawnAmounts[0].amount and withdrawnAmounts[1].amount match expectations before completing the burn.

Title: Concentrated liquidity pool initialization missing sqrtPrice bounds check causes permanent denial-of-service via TickMath revert
Impact: HIGH
Protocol: Concentrated Liquidity AMM

The pool constructor accepts an arbitrary initial price (uint160 sqrtPriceX96) decoded from deployment data without validating it falls within the valid TickMath range [MIN_SQRT_RATIO, MAX_SQRT_RATIO). Any subsequent operation that derives the current tick via TickMath.getTickAtSqrtRatio() will revert permanently if the stored price is out of bounds, bricking the pool.

File: ConcentratedLiquidityPool.sol

111 : constructor(bytes memory deployData, IMasterDeployer masterDeployer) {
112 :     (address token0, address token1, uint24 swapFee, uint160 sqrtPriceX96, uint24 tickSpacing) = abi.decode(
113 :         deployData,
114 :         (address, address, uint24, uint160, uint24)
115 :     );
116 :     require(token0 != address(0), "ZERO_ADDRESS");
117 :     require(swapFee <= MAX_FEE, "INVALID_SWAP_FEE");
118 :     // BUG: no validation on sqrtPriceX96
119 :@>  price = sqrtPriceX96;  // stored without checking MIN_SQRT_RATIO <= sqrtPriceX96 < MAX_SQRT_RATIO
120 : }

TickMath.getTickAtSqrtRatio() enforces:
    require(sqrtPriceX96 >= MIN_SQRT_RATIO && sqrtPriceX96 < MAX_SQRT_RATIO);

If price is stored outside this range, every call to swap(), mint(), burn(), and rangeFeeGrowth() that internally calls TickMath will revert. Since the constructor runs only once, there is no recovery path.

Impact: Permanent DoS — all user funds directed to the pool are locked forever at zero cost to the attacker or misconfigured deployer.

Recommended mitigation:
    require(
        sqrtPriceX96 >= TickMath.MIN_SQRT_RATIO && sqrtPriceX96 < TickMath.MAX_SQRT_RATIO,
        "INVALID_PRICE"
    );
    price = sqrtPriceX96;

Title: Fee growth inside range calculation uses wrong tick boundary reference producing incorrect fee deltas for in-range liquidity providers
Impact: HIGH
Protocol: Concentrated Liquidity AMM

The rangeFeeGrowth() function uses nearestTick (the last initialized tick at or below current price, updated only on tick crossings) instead of the actual current pool tick when evaluating fee growth boundary conditions. Between tick crossings, nearestTick can lag behind the true price tick, causing the boundary conditions to be evaluated from the wrong side and producing incorrect fee deltas.

File: ConcentratedLiquidityPool.sol

601 : function rangeFeeGrowth(int24 lowerTick, int24 upperTick) public view
602 :     returns (uint256 feeGrowthInside0, uint256 feeGrowthInside1)
603 : {
604 :@>  int24 currentTick = nearestTick;  // BUG: nearestTick is stale between crossings
605 :     // correct: should derive currentTick from pool.price via TickMath.getTickAtSqrtRatio(price)
606 :
607 :     if (lowerTick <= currentTick) {   // wrong boundary — evaluates against stale tick
608 :         feeGrowthBelow0 = lower.feeGrowthOutside0;
609 :     } else {
610 :         feeGrowthBelow0 = feeGrowthGlobal0 - lower.feeGrowthOutside0;
611 :     }
612 :     if (currentTick < upperTick) {
613 :         feeGrowthAbove0 = upper.feeGrowthOutside0;
614 :     } else {
615 :         feeGrowthAbove0 = feeGrowthGlobal0 - upper.feeGrowthOutside0;
616 :     }
617 :     feeGrowthInside0 = feeGrowthGlobal0 - feeGrowthBelow0 - feeGrowthAbove0;
618 : }

When nearestTick != actual price tick, the feeGrowthBelow and feeGrowthAbove boundary conditions select accumulator values from the wrong side. This causes in-range LPs to accrue incorrect fees. In edge cases the subtraction at line 617 reverts due to underflow, permanently locking positions.

Impact: LPs accrue incorrect fee amounts; edge cases cause permanent position lock.

Recommended mitigation: Replace nearestTick with TickMath.getTickAtSqrtRatio(price) in rangeFeeGrowth() to use the actual current pool tick.
